<HL> Wal-Mart's Earnings
Rose 40%, Sales 35%
In Fiscal 2nd Quarter</HL>
<DD> 08/12/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> WMT
RETAILING (RET)
EARNINGS (ERN) </IN>
<DATELINE> BENTONVILLE, Ark.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc. reported net income for its fiscal second quarter ended July 31 rose 40% to $134.1 million, or 24 cents a share, from $95.9 million, or 17 cents a share, a year ago. 

   Sales of the discount retailer increased 35% to $3.73 billion from $2.77 billion. 

   For the six months, net income jumped 44% to $244.5 million, or 43 cents a share, from $169.3 million, or 30 cents a share. 
Sales increased 35% to $6.94 billion from $5.11 billion. 

   Sam Walton, chairman, said Wal-Mart's results were "above-budget" and that the chain is "well-positioned to meet our objectives for the remaining six months of this year." 

   In the second quarter, the company opened 27 new Wal-Mart stores, 21 Sam's Wholesale Clubs and two dot Discount Drug stores. 

   Wal-Mart shares closed yesterday at $42, up $1.875, in New York Stock Exchange composite trading. 

</TEXT>
